## The Structural Pattern
These failures share one assumption: that obvious friction points are the true bottlenecks, and that automation itself creates velocity even without measurement, guardrails, or sequencing. Multiple scenarios assume current pain is well-understood when the plan shows little baseline data: no flake-rate metric, no PR flow decomposition, no release failure taxonomy, no eligibility rules for auto-approval. So this is mainly a **sequencing problem with execution consequences**: the team is trying to automate before instrumenting and standardizing. The plan should change: add a short diagnostics phase, gate each automation behind safety metrics, and remove any immediate production-facing auto-approval/auto-deploy behavior.

## The One Test
Run a **2-week engineering flow baseline study** next week across one representative service/repo. Instrument every PR from open to prod: PR size, time to first review, total wait time, review rounds, CI duration, rerun count, flake failures, deploy lead time, and incident-causing changes. In parallel, manually classify the top 20 delayed PRs and last 10 deployment incidents by root cause. At the end, choose **one** bottleneck with quantified impact and trial the smallest safe intervention there. This single test would tell you whether review triage, test work, or deploy automation is actually the first lever — and whether the current plan should proceed, be reordered, or be cut.
